+# BossTerm Deep Technical Review: Security, Performance, and Portable VFS Strategy
+
+Date: 2026-02-26  
+Scope reviewed: `bossterm-core-mpp`, `compose-ui`, `bossterm-app`, build/update pipeline, settings/state persistence.
+
+## 1) Executive summary (least effort, most change)
+
+If you only do **five** things this cycle, do these:
+
+1. **Add integrity verification (SHA-256 + signed manifest) to updates before install** — currently update flow relies on HTTPS and filename checks but does not cryptographically verify payloads.
+2. **Stop persisting or shell-echoing privileged secrets (`BOSSTERM_SUDO_PWD`) in command strings** — move to OS credential store + stdin-only ephemeral token handoff.
+3. **Fix shell command construction for path/context commands (`git -C`, `cd "..." && gh ...`)** — use argument arrays or strong shell escaping utility to avoid command injection on crafted paths.
+4. **Make settings writes atomic + permission-hardened** (`0600`, temp+rename) to prevent corruption and reduce local secret exposure.
+5. **Introduce a portable workspace layer (VFS abstraction + sync engine) with local-first journal**; defer true 9P wire protocol until phase 2. You can get 80% of user value quickly with an abstraction-first design.
+
+These are high-leverage because they harden core trust boundaries (update, privilege, command execution, persistence) while preparing the app for cross-OS “bring my stuff with me” behavior.
+
+---
+
+## 2) Architectural coverage and threat/perf model
+
+### 2.1 Main architectural areas
+
+- **Terminal core/emulation** (`bossterm-core-mpp`): parsing/terminal state, model buffers, text snapshots.
+- **Desktop platform services** (`compose-ui` desktop): PTY process lifecycle, filesystem helpers, URL opening, notifications.
+- **User/workspace state** (`compose-ui` settings/theme managers): JSON persistence under `~/.bossterm`.
+- **Tooling integration** (AI/VCS/shell/custom tools): command generation and execution path.
+- **Auto-update subsystem** (GitHub API download + platform installer scripts).
+- **Packaging/build scripts** (signing/notarization/package assembly).
+
+### 2.2 Trust boundaries
+
+- Untrusted terminal output → hyperlink parser/URL opener.
+- Untrusted local FS/path state → generated shell command strings.
+- Network-delivered update artifacts → local privileged install path.
+- User-configured commands/scripts → shell execution.
+- Sensitive local config state → plain JSON files and process environment.
+
+### 2.3 Performance hot regions
+
+- Render/event loop path performing repeated filesystem/process checks.
+- Process helpers with many short-lived subprocesses (`which`, `git`, `lsof`, `pgrep`).
+- Settings/theme write/read patterns with frequent whole-file rewrites.
+- Update download/progress loops and coroutine scope usage.
+
+---
+
+## 3) Findings by area
+
+## 3.1 Update/security pipeline (Critical)
+
+### What is strong
+- Uses TLS via Ktor clients and request timeouts.
+- Checks file existence/extensions and performs canonical path checks.
+- Implements basic downgrade prevention via version extraction from filenames.
+
+### Gaps
+1. **No cryptographic artifact verification before install**.
+   - Current checks validate extension/path/version, not authenticity.
+   - A supply-chain compromise at release host/CDN/account level can still deliver valid-looking malicious artifacts.
+
+2. **Canonical temp-dir validation is warning-only for out-of-dir file**.
+   - File outside expected temp location logs warning rather than hard fail.
+
+3. **Install scripts execute with elevated permissions on some paths** without signed metadata trust chain.
+
+### Low-effort remediations
+- Add release asset sidecar (`.sha256`) and verify hash before install.
+- Add signed manifest (minisign/cosign/sigstore) for artifact + hash set and validate in app.
+- Change out-of-dir canonical check from warning to hard failure unless explicit override flag.
+
+### Impact
+- **Security risk reduction: very high**.
+- **Engineering effort: low-to-medium** (mostly updater module + release CI).
+
+---
+
+## 3.2 Command construction and injection surface (High)
+
+### Risk vectors
+1. **String-built shell commands with interpolated working directory/arguments** for Git/GH helper flows.
+2. **Tool command builders concatenate command + flags** in plain strings.
+3. **Generated installation commands include dynamic shell fragments**.
+
+### Why this matters
+If any interpolated field contains shell metacharacters or quotes (especially path values), this can produce command confusion/injection when sent to a shell-backed PTY.
+
+### Low-effort remediations
+- Introduce `ShellEscaper.escapePosix()/escapePowershell()` and route all interpolated tokens through it.
+- Prefer process invocation with argv arrays where possible (for non-interactive helper checks).
+- Add centralized “safe command builder” for menu-generated commands.
+
+### Quick tests to add
+- Unit tests for cwd containing quotes, backticks, `$()`, semicolons.
+- Property-style tests for escaping round-trip behavior.
+
+---
+
+## 3.3 Secrets and privileged install handling (High)
+
+### Findings
+- Install command flow references `BOSSTERM_SUDO_PWD` and feeds it into `sudo -S` via shell script text.
+- This increases exposure in process environments, shell history risk (depending on integration), and diagnostic/log leakage risk.
+
+### Low-effort remediations
+- Store privileged token in OS-native keychain/credential manager abstraction.
+- Pass password only through short-lived stdin stream to child process (never env var, never persisted to disk).
+- Scrub related variables after process completion and on failure paths.
+
+### Outcome
+- Strongly reduces accidental credential disclosure and lateral-process harvesting risk.
+
+---
+
+## 3.4 Settings/storage resilience and security (Medium)
+
+### Findings
+- Settings manager writes JSON directly using `writeText` and logs location.
+- No explicit file permission hardening; no atomic temp-write+rename strategy.
+- Corruption risk on crash/interruption during write.
+
+### Low-effort remediations
+- Write to temp file in same dir, `fsync`, atomic rename.
+- Set/create permissions to user-only (where supported).
+- Add backup rotation (`settings.json.bak`) and checksum marker.
+
+### Performance side-effect
+Atomic writes + debounce save calls also reduce unnecessary write amplification.
+
+---
+
+## 3.5 URL/hyperlink and local-file exposure (Medium)
+
+### Findings
+- Hyperlink/file path resolution canonicalizes and checks existence (good baseline).
+- URL opening ultimately delegates to OS open handlers; scheme restrictions should be explicit and centralized.
+
+### Low-effort remediations
+- Add explicit allowlist for URL schemes (`https`, `http`, `file`, optionally `mailto`).
+- Add safe prompt/confirmation for local file opens from terminal output (configurable trust mode).
+- Add telemetry counter (local only) for blocked dangerous schemes.
+
+---
+
+## 3.6 Process lifecycle and concurrency/perf (Medium)
+
+### Findings
+- PTY service does substantial work correctly (UTF-8 boundary handling, graceful/forced kill).
+- However ancillary helpers (`pgrep`, `lsof`, repeated `which` checks, git probes) can be frequent and expensive under heavy tab churn.
+- Update service contains `GlobalScope` usage patterns which are harder to lifecycle-control and can leak work across UI teardown.
+
+### Low-effort remediations
+- Cache command-availability probes with TTL (e.g., 30–120s).
+- Debounce cwd polling and batch process metadata reads.
+- Replace `GlobalScope` with structured scope tied to app/window lifecycle.
+
+---
+
+## 3.7 Dependency and supply-chain posture (Medium)
+
+### Findings
+- Modern stack overall (Kotlin 2.1.x, Compose 1.9.x, Ktor 3.3.x, coroutines 1.10.x).
+- No visible automated SBOM + vulnerability gate in reviewed scripts.
+
+### Low-effort remediations
+- Generate SBOM in CI (CycloneDX Gradle plugin).
+- Add OSS vulnerability scanner gate (OSV/Dependency-Check/Snyk/Trivy in CI).
+- Enforce dependency lockfiles/verification metadata for Gradle.
+
+---
+
+## 4) Performance optimization opportunities (ranked by ROI)
+
+## P0 (high ROI, low effort)
+1. **Command/process probe cache**
+   - Cache `which`, `git repo` checks, branch lookups for short TTL.
+2. **Settings save debounce**
+   - Coalesce rapid updates into a single atomic write.
+3. **Structured coroutine scope in updater/services**
+   - Prevent background work leaks, improve shutdown latency.
+
+## P1 (high ROI, medium effort)
+1. **Background indexing for hyperlinks/path checks**
+   - Keep render thread free; incremental/cache invalidation on cwd change.
+2. **Batch VCS status refresh**
+   - Single scheduled refresh per tab/window rather than per interaction.
+3. **Metrics hooks**
+   - Add lightweight timers around process checks, render frame, update download, settings I/O.
+
+## P2 (medium ROI, medium/high effort)
+1. **Unify process helper service**
+   - Reuse subprocess channels where practical.
+2. **Incremental state persistence model**
+   - Journal-based settings/events then compaction.
+
+---
+
+## 5) Portable VFS (virtio-9p style) strategy
+
+Your stated goal: when a user uses BossTerm on Windows and later on macOS, “all my stuff comes with me.”
+
+A direct kernel-level 9P implementation is not required to deliver user value in BossTerm. The practical path is:
+
+## 5.1 Product interpretation
+Portable “stuff” likely means:
+- terminal profiles, themes, keybindings,
+- snippets/history/workflows,
+- optional workspace metadata and session context,
+- optionally selected files/projects.
+
+This maps well to a **user-space syncable VFS abstraction** first, protocol later.
+
+## 5.2 Proposed architecture (phaseable)
+
+### Layer A — `BossVfs` interface (now)
+Define a platform-agnostic API:
+- `open/read/write/list/stat/mkdir/remove/rename/watch/sync`.
+- URI namespaces: `local://`, `portable://`, `cache://`, `remote://`.
+- Metadata: inode-like ID, version vector, content hash, mtime, permissions map.
+
+### Layer B — local-first object store + metadata journal (now)
+- Content-addressed blobs + SQLite/JSON metadata index.
+- Append-only operation journal for conflict recovery.
+- Compression and optional encryption-at-rest.
+
+### Layer C — sync transport plugin (soon)
+- Start with robust HTTPS sync (chunked upload/download + manifests).
+- Add provider adapters (Git repo backend, S3/WebDAV, self-host).
+- CRDT-lite or LWW+conflict files for merges.
+
+### Layer D — 9P-style protocol adapter (later)
+- Expose the same `BossVfs` over a 9P-like session for advanced integration.
+- Keep it optional and isolated; do not block product value on it.
+
+## 5.3 Why this is “least effort, most change”
+- You can ship cross-OS portability after Layer A+B+C without kernel dependencies.
+- 9P compatibility becomes a transport concern, not a foundational blocker.
+- Existing settings/state code naturally migrates into `portable://config/...` paths.
+
+## 5.4 Data model suggestions
+- `portable://config/settings.json`
+- `portable://themes/*.json`
+- `portable://profiles/*.json`
+- `portable://history/events.log`
+- `portable://workspaces/<id>/...`
+
+Each file has:
+- `contentHash`, `logicalClock`, `deviceId`, `lastWriter`, `encryptionState`.
+
+## 5.5 Conflict strategy
+- Default LWW for low-risk files (UI prefs).
+- Three-way merge for structured JSON where possible.
+- For non-mergeable files: create sibling conflict copy + notification.
+
+## 5.6 Security model for portable VFS
+- End-to-end encryption option with user passphrase-derived key.
+- Per-device key wrapping for convenience mode.
+- Signed manifest per sync transaction.
+- Replay protection via monotonic operation IDs.
+
+## 5.7 Migration plan (practical)
+
+1. Build `BossVfs` interface + local adapter.
+2. Move `SettingsManager` and theme managers to VFS-backed repository API.
+3. Add sync daemon (manual trigger first, then interval/background).
+4. Introduce selective sync UI (“what travels”).
+5. Add optional 9P-style adapter for power users/integration.
+
+---
+
+## 6) Prioritized action plan
+
+## Next 2 weeks (hardening sprint)
+- Implement update SHA/signature verification.
+- Introduce safe command builder + path escaping tests.
+- Remove env-password pattern; add credential provider abstraction.
+- Atomic settings write + permissions hardening.
+
+## Next 4–6 weeks (portability foundation)
+- Introduce `BossVfs` API and local object/journal store.
+- Route settings/themes/profiles through repository layer.
+- Add initial cloud sync adapter + conflict UX for settings.
+
+## 2–3 months (advanced portability)
+- Extend sync to session/workspace artifacts.
+- Optional 9P-style protocol bridge.
+- Add observability dashboard for sync health and perf.
+
+---
+
+## 7) Risk register summary
+
+- **Critical**: Update artifact authenticity not cryptographically enforced.
+- **High**: Command construction injection surface via interpolated shell strings.
+- **High**: Privileged credential handling via environment and shell scripts.
+- **Medium**: Non-atomic settings writes and weak local secret hardening.
+- **Medium**: Ancillary subprocess overhead and lifecycle leaks.
+- **Medium**: Missing automated supply-chain gates in CI.
+
+---
+
+## 8) Final recommendation
+
+Treat this as two parallel tracks:
+
+1. **Trust hardening track (immediate)**: updater verification + command safety + secret handling + atomic persistence.
+2. **Portability track (strategic)**: `BossVfs` abstraction with local-first sync, then optional 9P adapter.
+
+This approach keeps engineering cost controlled while producing visible user value quickly, and it aligns with the cross-OS portability vision without overcommitting to a protocol-specific implementation too early.
+
